<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<p>
Let \(\{W_i\}_{i=1}^n\) be a
finite set of
<a knowl="defs/vec/sub">subspaces</a> of a vector space \(V\).
</p>
<p>
The <b>sum</b> of these subspaces is
\[\sum_{i=1}^nW_i := \left\{\sum_{i=1}^nw_i: w_i\in W_i\right\}.\]
</p>
<p>
This forms a subspace of \(V\).
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
Let \(\alpha, \beta\in\mathbf F\) and let \(u, v\in\sum_{i=1}^nW_i\).
Write \(u = \sum_{i=1}^nu_i, v = \sum_{i=1}^nv_i\)
where \(u_i, v_i\in W_i\).
Then
\[\alpha u + \beta v = \alpha\sum_{i=1}^nu_i + \beta\sum_{i=1}^nv_i
= \sum_{i=1}^n(\alpha u_i + \beta v_i).\]
Since each \(W_i\) is a subspace,
we have \(\alpha u_i + \beta v_i\in W_i\).
Hence, \(\alpha u + \beta v\in\sum_{i=1}^nW_i\).
</details>
</p>
<p>
The sum \(\sum_{i=1}^nW_i\) is called a <b>direct sum</b>
\[(\text{and written}\;\bigoplus_{i=1}^nW_i)\]
if the only way to express 0 is with
\((w_1,\dots,w_n) = (0,\dots,0)\).
</p>
</body>
</html>
